    <header>
        <h1>Non-Semantic vs Semantic Tags in HTML</h1>
    </header>
    <main>
        <section>
            <h2>What is the difference?</h2>
            <p>
                In HTML, <strong>semantic tags</strong> clearly describe their meaning and the type of content they contain, such as <code>&lt;header&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;article&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code>. These tags help browsers, developers, and assistive technologies understand the structure and purpose of the content.<br>
                <strong>Non-semantic tags</strong> like <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> do not convey any meaning about their contentâ€”they are used mainly for layout or styling purposes.
            </p>
        </section>
        <section>
            <h2>Benefits of Using Semantic Tags</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Improved Accessibility:</strong> Semantic tags provide context to assistive technologies, making web pages easier to navigate for users with disabilities.</li>
                <li><strong>Better SEO:</strong> Search engines can better understand and index your content, improving your site's visibility in search results.</li>
                <li><strong>Enhanced Readability:</strong> Semantic tags make the code easier to read and maintain for developers.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>
    </main>
